The Rivers State police command has dismissed one Sergeant Bitrus Osaiah, after standing Orderly Room trial for killing a female colleague, Sergeant Lovender Elekwachi, at Eneka Roundabout in Ohio/Akpor local government area of the state. Osaiah, who was attached to the Rivers State Taskforce on Street Trading and Illegal Motor Parks, shot and killed Elekwachi, who was on duty at the roundabout on April 23, 2020, while enforcing market closure directive on COVID-19 order by the state government. The commissioner of Police, Joseph Mukan, disclosed this while speaking with newsmen shortly after paying a condolence visit to the family of the deceased female Sergeant at Isu-Ozuzu Community in Etche local government area of the state. Mukan, who said Osaiah has been handed over to the court for trial, said he has directed the withdrawal of all policemen attached to the Rivers State Taskforce on Street Trading and Illegal Motor-Parks. The police commissioner said: “The Police Sergeant, who pulled the trigger have been dismissed and handed to court for prosecution. We cannot hand him over to court if we have not dismissed him, I can categorically tell you that he would be in court soon.” He promised that the Command will cater for the children of the late female Police Sergeant, saying that the police was deeply pained at the untimely demise of their colleague who died in active duty. Speaking on behalf of the deceased family, Engr. Joseph Amaechi demanded that the police hierarchy should provide scholarships to the children of the late Elekwachi and pay proper compensation to the poor family since the deceased is the bread winner of the family.